subSubSection.paragraph:
Aedeagus : length 1.13 mm ; elongate shape; with fused paramere, almost as long as 1/2 of the aedeagus length, outline straight; apex convex, subacute in ventral view and more distinctly acute in lateral view; basal half slightly wider than apical half, although in lateral view this difference in width is more noticeable; internal sac slightly visible (
Fig. 24g
).

Diagnosis of the 

platypterus

group

: without any of the male sexual structures indicated in the previous groups, except 

B. aenigmaticus

which has the metatrochanter acute apically; head without temporal carina; mandibles with a middle tooth and a basal tooth well separated from each other, both in dorsal position (in two species the left mandible has two middle teeth close to each other, interspace C-shaped, in addition to the basal tooth; 
Fig. 9f
); head shape subquadrate or transverse (ratio length/width 0.76–0.97; 
Fig. 10d
); mandibles 0.75 to 1.4 times as long as cephalic length; tarsomeres somewhat flattened dorsally; aedeagus with reduced paramere (
Figs. 24h–l
, 
25a
).

paragraph.keyLead:
2(1) Elytra, legs and first four visible abdominal segments reddish (
Figs. 8a, c
)........................................ 3

- Elytra, legs and first four visible abdominal segments black (
Figs 8b, d, e
)........................................ 4

3(2) Cephalic dorsal surface with punctation less dense (
Fig. 8a
); dorsal rows of pronotum with five or six punctures (exceptionally seven in one or both rows) that cover 3/4 of the pronotal length (
Fig. 8a
); scutellum reddish to brown; male pregenital sternite slightly less deeply emarginate at posterior margin (
Fig. 16d
); aedeagus with apex moderately acute and with conspicuous internal sac (
Fig. 24h
)...................................................................... 

B. aenigmaticus

- Cephalic dorsal surface with punctation denser (

Figs. 
10g
, j

); dorsal rows of pronotum with seven to nine punctures that cover the main part of its length (
Fig. 10j
); scutellum black; male pregenital sternite slightly more deeply emarginate at posterior margin (
Fig. 16–o
); aedeagus with apex acute and internal sac slightly visible (
Fig. 24k
)...................... 

B. optatus

4(2) Last two visible abdominal segments reddish (
Fig. 8d
); left mandible with two middle teeth of small size very close to each other, interspace C-shaped (
Fig. 9f
); tarsomeres notably flattened dorsally; male pregenital sternite not emarginate at posterior margin (
Fig. 15f
); male genital sternite moderately elongate (2.6 times longer than wide) (
Fig. 20h
); aedeagus as in 

Fig. 24–l.......................................................................................... 

B


. platypterus

- Entire body black (
Figs. 8b, e
); left mandible with a basal tooth and a middle tooth well separated from each other (
Fig. 10f
); tarsomeres moderately flattened dorsally; male pregenital sternite weakly emarginate at posterior margin (
Figs. 16e, f
); male genital sternite and aedeagus different from above........................................................... 5

keyLead.keyStep:
5(4) Head transverse, slightly ovoid, with convex vertex, in lateral view without microsculpture like irregular lines under and behind each eye (
Fig. 10f
); male mandibles as long as, or longer than head; eyes nearly 0.5 times the cephalic lateral length; body surface glossy (
Fig. 8b
); male genital sternite short (2.14 times as long as wide), very asymmetrical (
Fig. 20f
); aedeagus as in 

Fig. 24j................................................................................... 

B


. nigerrimus
